    295 Chapter 4: Fluid-Structure Interaction Geometric Eulerian Boundary Conditions Main Index Geometric Eulerian Boundary Conditions Problem Description For many applications, the Euler modelling can be simplified by using the MESH Generator entry. However, this method has some shortcomings with regard to the definition of the boundary conditions at the boundaries of the Euler meshes. In the past if flow boundaries were required one had to create BCSEG with Patran. Since BCSEGs only support CHEXA’s, the only way to define flow boundaries for MESH, BOX was to define a PORFLOW entry and a COUPLE entry. Geometric Euler Boundary Condition entries allow to directly prescribe boundary conditions on the boundaries of the Euler domain. This functionality also supports Euler domains consisting of CHEXA’s. Running the simulation with different mesh-sizes is much easier, since the creation of CHEXA’s and BCSEGs by Patran/SimX can be avoided. The geometric boundary entries are FLOW, FLOWDEF, BARRIER and FLOWT. The first two allow the assignment of a boundary condition to all Eulerian boundary faces pointing in a certain direction. FLOW allows a general flow boundary condition, whereas BARRIER applies barrier for euler mesh transportation boundary condition. The FLOWT assign flow and time dependent flow conditions to all parts of Eulerian boundary faces that are within a given square. Geometric boundary condition can only apply to the boundary of the domain. An internal BARRIER cannot be defined by geometric boundary conditions, which is defined as obstruct to fluid transportation. BARRIER overrules FLOW and FLOWT definition. Also, the example Modeling Blast Wave using 1-D Spherical Symmetry Method illustrates the use of FLOWDEF. This example illustrates use of Geometric Euler Boundary condition in the Vortex shedding with skin friction calculation. For a description of the problem, refer to Vortex Shedding with Skin Friction. SOL 700 Model For this example, a 2-D model is used with an Euler mesh of 0.8 x 0.8 m and element thickness of 0.01 m. The number of elements in X and Y directions is 90. The diameter of the cylinder is 0.1 m. The cylinder is modeled as a rigid coupling surface that can’t move. The initial conditions in the Euler region are: Specific internal energy = 2.E+5 J/kg Density = 1.3 kg/m3 The boundary conditions at the borders of the Euler mesh are as follows: ï®At the left side, an Inflow boundary with the following data Specific internal energy = 2.E+5 J/kg

    and Centre of Gravity (ZCG) displacement is shown in the figure below. To extend the Coulomb friction model to account for cohesive conditions: PARAM,COHESION,8e+10,8e+5,2.0 is added. This allows soil to stick to some extend to the wedge that is pulled up. The 8e+10 is the maximum tensile stress. The 8e+5 and 2.0 describe a viscous-like friction law. This law specifies a friction stress that is linear in the relative tangential velocity between material and wedge. Under compressive conditions the Coulomb friction model will be used as specified on the COUPLE entry. Only for tensile conditions will the model be used as specified on the COHESION entry.
